Project 1 - Clean/Train Housing Dataset

By Christian Garzon

Intro

For my Project I plan on attempting to train a model in hopes of predicting the Sale Price of the houses. In order to do this I will first clean as much of the data as possible and pick certain variables to train the model on depending on each variables predicting power (correlation w/ Sale Price). My focus will be on the data wrangling and cleaning, trying different methods to try to make the data as clean as possible without changing too much about the original data. After I do this I will choose the best predictors and attempt to create a model using these predictors, in doing so I should be able to predict a house value within a reasonable margin of error.

Cleaning the Data

To train the model I must first clean up a lot of the data. I will do this by looking at all the missing data and trying to find if there is a reason for the data to be missing or if the it is at random. I will do this by counting all the NaN in each variable and creating a list of each variable containing missing data.

The missing data found in the dataset can be found in the following variables:

  • LotFrontage: Linear feet of street connected to property
  • Alley: Type of alley access
  • MasVnrType: Masonry veneer type
  • MasVnrArea: Masonry veneer area in square feet
  • BsmtQual: Height of the basement
  • BsmtCond: General condition of the basement
  • BsmtExposure: Walkout or garden level basement walls
  • BsmtFinType1: Quality of basement finished area
  • BsmtFinType2: Quality of second finished area (if present)
  • Electrical: Electrical system
  • FireplaceQu: Fireplace quality
  • GarageType: Garage location
  • GarageYrBlt: Year garage was built
  • GarageFinish: Interior finish of the garage
  • GarageQual: Garage quality
  • GarageCond: Garage condition
  • PoolQC: Pool quality
  • Fence: Fence quality
  • MiscFeature: Miscellaneous feature not covered in other categories

Since both of these have a decent correlation I am inclined to keep them in the dataset, however since they might be highly correlated with each other since they are both related to fireplaces I fear creating noise during the training process. To avoid this I have decided for categories that are highly related, meaning if they are about similar features, I will only choose the category that has the most correlation to keep my dataset more simple. Although this is probably not the preferred method this will help keep the process and dataset more simple.

Based off their correlations with sale price it seems quality has a higher predicitive power than quantity so I will keep quality.

To ensure this only happens once and theres no other discreprencies I first compare the ids from the Miscellaneous items with value and compare it to the ids of all existing miscellaneous items.

Garage Variables

Since all the Garage variables are missing the same amount of data points they are likely missing the same data points and can be replaced with 'No Garage'. The data points missing are from the following variables:

  • GarageType: Garage location
  • GarageYrBlt: Year garage was built
  • GarageFinish: Interior finish of the garage
  • GarageArea: Size of garage in square feet
  • GarageQual: Garage quality
  • GarageCond: Garage condition

To ensure they are the same data points I will check the shape of a dataframe made of two variables at once. If the shape remains the same then they are the same missing values, if the shapes are not equal then they have different missing values.

Reflection

For the data wrangling and cleaning part of this project, I am content with many of my methods and approaches to clean the dataset. One improvement I thought of while working through the cleaning, throughout the process I used different methods to either erase or replace data. While this was a good for discovering and trying new ways to clean data, I think for future projects I should make a more strict protocol when it comes to missing data that way each missing point is handled in the same way because right now my methods were a little diverse.

For the data training I left much to be desired. If I had more time I would want to go and try to convert all the categorical values to numerical values if possible and also have a more rigorous method of choosing the variables which the model was trained on. The error of my model is much higher than I desired. For my next project I plan on focusing more on the training side in hopes of seeing improvement and more understanding on that front.
